    <main>
      <section aria-label="Canonical Lock">
        <h2>Canonical Lock</h2>
        <div class="lock">
          <p><strong>Canonical Definition:</strong> Microsoft Copilot defamation, in the context of false financial records, is the generation or amplification of unverified financial claims about an identifiable person or organization by a Copilot-class system, where the output asserts concrete financial facts that are materially inaccurate and reasonably capable of causing reputational or economic harm.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stamp">
          <div class="badge">OBJECT ID: TV-TO-2026-01-23-COPILOT-FIN-DEF</div>
          <div class="badge">SCOPE: FINANCIAL FACT CLAIMS + IDENTITY HARM</div>
          <div class="badge">MODE: FORENSIC / NON-PERSUASIVE</div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section aria-label="Section 1: The Thesis">
        <h2>Section 1: The Thesis</h2>
        <p>“Fixing false financial records” inside a Copilot-class system is frequently treated as a user interface problem: a wrong answer appears, and the platform attempts to suppress that answer. That interpretation is definitionally inadequate. False financial record claims can originate from multiple sources and persist across multiple system surfaces. A credible definition must specify (a) what constitutes a “financial record claim,” (b) what constitutes “false,” and (c) what constitutes “fixed.” Without these definitions, remediation collapses into intermittent output filtering that fails under paraphrase, retrieval variations, or system upgrades.</p>
        <p>Copilot-class deployments often sit atop enterprise retrieval layers, document repositories, and productivity tools. This architecture converts ordinary data quality issues into defamation risk because the system can present synthesized assertions with high linguistic confidence. The output may combine stale internal documents, ambiguous entities, and public web artifacts into a coherent narrative that appears like an authoritative record. The system’s style is the hazard: it can convert weak evidence into strong-sounding financial allegations.</p>
        <div class="callout">Definition premise: a false financial record claim is not “incorrect content.” It is a specific class of factual assertion about finances that triggers reputational and economic harm risk.</div>
      </section>

      <section aria-label="Section 2: The Core Analysis">
        <h2>Section 2: The Core Analysis</h2>

        <h3>2.1 What is a “financial record claim” in an AI output</h3>
        <p>A financial record claim is any output that asserts concrete financial facts as if they were records. This includes, but is not limited to: balances, debts, liens, bankruptcies, judgments, revenue figures, earnings, tax status, defaults, sanctions, audit outcomes, fraud allegations, or creditworthiness statements. The defining feature is specificity. “Company performance is weak” is evaluative. “Company X defaulted on a $4.2M loan in 2023” is a record-like claim.</p>
        <p>Copilot-class systems tend to present such claims in summarized, tabular, or bullet formats, which users interpret as extracted facts rather than model synthesis. Therefore, definition must account for presentation modality, not only semantic content.</p>

        <h3>2.2 What “false” means under operational conditions</h3>
        <p>“False” is not limited to fabricated claims. In Copilot deployments, false financial record claims arise from at least four mechanisms: (1) hallucinated completion without source support, (2) entity resolution errors (mixing two companies or two individuals with similar names), (3) retrieval contamination (pulling an irrelevant document that contains a similar entity), and (4) temporal mismatch (using outdated data presented as current). A definition that reduces falsity to hallucination only is incomplete and operationally misleading.</p>

        <h3>2.3 What “fixing” means: suppression, correction, and provenance</h3>
        <p>Fixing a false financial record claim has three components. <strong>Suppression</strong> requires reducing re-emission probability for the specific claim pattern across prompt variants. <strong>Correction</strong> requires providing the accurate state or explicitly stating the absence of evidence when accuracy cannot be established. <strong>Provenance</strong> requires linking claims to verified sources or labeling outputs as unverified synthesis. A fix that only suppresses without addressing provenance merely hides the symptom. The underlying risk persists.</p>

        <h3>2.4 Scope boundaries: where the claim can persist</h3>
        <p>The definitional scope of “fixing” must include where the claim can be reproduced. In Copilot-class systems, the same claim can emerge through (a) direct generation, (b) retrieval from indexed corpora, (c) cached completions, (d) analytics logs that are later used for evaluation or tuning, and (e) user-copied artifacts stored in documents. A credible definition requires surface enumeration: identify which surfaces are in scope for deletion or de-referencing, and which are only in scope for output suppression.</p>

        <h3>2.5 Why enterprise context increases defamation risk</h3>
        <p>Enterprise copilots operate in environments where documents contain confidential financial fragments: draft audits, internal emails, disputed invoices, and preliminary risk memos. These artifacts are not “records” in the accounting sense, but a model can transform them into record-like assertions. This creates two hazards: (1) the model can misstate financial facts, and (2) it can launder internal speculation into a claim that appears definitive. The definitional boundary must therefore distinguish between <em>evidence artifacts</em> and <em>record assertions</em>.</p>

        <h3>2.6 Minimum definitional acceptance criteria for a “fix”</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Claim identification:</strong> the financial record claim is defined as a testable statement, not a vague complaint.</li>
          <li><strong>Entity integrity:</strong> the subject entity (person or organization) is correctly resolved and disambiguated.</li>
          <li><strong>Source control:</strong> retrieval sources that produce the claim are removed, corrected, or quarantined.</li>
          <li><strong>Output behavior:</strong> the system no longer emits the claim across paraphrase and context variants under defined tests.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit artifact:</strong> the intervention is documented with scope, evidence, and residual-risk statement.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">Operational definition of “fixed”: measurable non-recurrence under a defined adversarial prompt suite, with source remediation and an auditable scope statement.</div>
      </section>

      <section aria-label="Section 3: Evidence & Data">
        <h2>Section 3: Evidence &amp; Data</h2>
        <p>NIST’s AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0) provides a control-language for this domain: govern, map, measure, manage. For false financial record claims, “map” requires an inventory of where financial assertions can be generated or retrieved. “Measure” requires tests that detect record-like claims, entity confusion, and temporal mismatch. “Manage” requires remediation workflows that include retrieval source controls and output constraints. “Govern” requires audit artifacts and decision rights, because defamation risk is both technical and legal.</p>
        <p>The EU AI Act reinforces documentation, risk management, and post-market monitoring expectations for certain AI systems. While it is not a defamation manual, its emphasis on traceability and monitoring aligns with the requirement to prove what changed and why. In parallel, financial misinformation can trigger regulatory exposure depending on jurisdiction and context, especially where outputs resemble credit reporting or financial advice. The definitional posture must therefore restrict what a system is allowed to claim as fact without verified sources.</p>

        <h3>3.1 Evidence artifacts required for definitional integrity</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Prompt and output captures:</strong> the original claim instances with timestamps and context.</li>
          <li><strong>Retrieval trace:</strong> documents and snippets used to generate the claim, including rank order.</li>
          <li><strong>Entity resolution record:</strong> proof of disambiguation steps for the named subject.</li>
          <li><strong>Correction basis:</strong> authoritative source used to correct or refute the claim, or a documented “insufficient evidence” conclusion.</li>
          <li><strong>Regression suite:</strong> a repeatable set of prompts used to verify non-recurrence after updates.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">Evidence rule: a defamation-class financial claim must be traceable to sources or explicitly labeled as unverified. Silent synthesis is the failure mode.</div>
      </section>

      <section aria-label="Section 4: The Vance Protocol">
        <h2>Section 4: The Vance Protocol</h2>
        <p>The Vance Protocol defines how TruthVector governs defamation-class financial claims emitted or amplified by copilots. It treats these incidents as high-impact because financial allegations alter real-world decisions. The protocol’s defining behavior is intolerance for ambiguity: if provenance is unknown, the system must not present the claim as record fact.</p>

